Let \{X_{n}:n\geq 1\} denote i.i.d. \mathcal {X}-valued r.v. with distribution P_{X}. Then,


\begin {align*}
 \lim _{n\to \infty }-\frac {1}{n}\log  p_{X^{n}}(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}) &= \lim _{n \to  \infty } -\frac {1}{n} \log  \prod _{i = 1}^{n} P_X(X_i) \\
 &= \mathbb {E}_{X \sim  p_X}[-\log  p_X(X)] \\ 
 &= H(X)
\end {align*}

Equivalently, for large n

  \begin {align*}
    \left |-\frac {1}{n} \log  p_{X^n}(X^n) - H(X)\right | \leq  \epsilon 
  \end {align*}

with high probability.

Fix an \epsilon >0. Then, an \epsilon -typical set with respect to the pmf p_{X}, denoted by A_{\epsilon }^{(n)}, is defined as
\left \{X^n \in  \mathcal {X}^n \mid  \left |-\frac {1}{n} \log  p_{X^n}(X^n) - H(X)\right | \leq  \epsilon  \right \}
Alternatively,
A_{\epsilon ^{(n)}} = \left \{X^n \in  \mathcal {X}^n \mid  2^{-n(H(X) + \epsilon )} \leq  p_{X^n}(X^n) \leq  2^{-n(H(X) - \epsilon )}\right \}

A coding system with parameters (n, \theta ) consist of an encoder and a decoder, where an encoder is a function
e: \mathcal {X}^n \to \{1, 2, \ldots , \theta \}
and a decoder is a function f: \{1, 2, \ldots , \theta \} \to \mathcal {X}^n

For the other direction, suppose we have some R achievable. By definition, for all \epsilon  > 0, for all sufficiently large n there exists a Coding system with parameters (n, \theta ) such that

  \begin {align*}
    \frac {\log  \theta }{n} < R + \epsilon , \quad  \mathbb {P}(\text {error}) < \epsilon 
  \end {align*}

Use Fano's Inequality to show this is not possible.

A randomized hypothesis test is a channel which takes in the data X and outputs a \{0,1\} valued random variable Z , where Z=i represents that the test declares that H_{i} is true, for i\in \{0,1\} .
X\sim P\longrightarrow \boxed {P_{Z|X}}\longrightarrow Z In some cases, it is sufficient to focus on non-randomized or deterministic tests, for which P_{\mathbb {Z}|X=x} is a delta function. That is, for a given realization of X , the output of the test is deterministic (it is equal to H_{0} or H_{1} with probability 1). Such deterministic tests can be equivalently represented by a function \Psi , or a subset B of the domain X :
\Psi (X)=\mathbf {1}_{B}(X)=\begin {cases}1,&\text {if}X\in B\\ 0,&\text {if}X\not \in B.\end {cases}

In any binary hypothesis testing problem, a test  P_{Z|X|}  can incur two types of errors:
\begin {align*}
   \pi _{1|0}(P_{Z|X})&=\mathbb {P}_{H_{0}}\ (Z=1) \quad  \text {(type-I error of false alarm rate)} \\
 \pi _{01}(P_{Z|X})&=\mathbb {P}_{H_{1}}\ (Z=0) \quad   \text {(type-II error or missed detection rate)}
.\end {align*}

Consider a hypothesis testing problem with observations  X^{n}\stackrel {\text {i.i.d.}}{\sim }P_{X} , with the null  H_{0} : P_{X} =P_{0}  and alternative  H_{1}:P_{X}=P_{1} . Then, the optimal NP test with level  \alpha \in  (0,1]  has the following structure:

 \Psi _{NP}^{*}(X^{n})=\begin {cases}1,&\text { if }L(X^{n})>\tau \\ \gamma ,&\text { if }L(X^{n})=\tau \\ 0,&\text { if }L(X^{n})<\tau .\end {cases} 

In the above display,  L(X^{n})  denotes the likelihood ratio  p_{1}(X^{n})/p_{0}(X^{n}) , and  \gamma \in [0,1]  and  \tau \geq 0  are constants that ensure  \pi _{1|0}(\Psi ^*_{NP})=\mathbb {P}_{H_{0}}(\Psi ^*_{NP}(X^{n})=1)=\alpha  . Namely, 
\tau  = \inf \{\tau  \mid  \alpha  \geq  \mathbb {P}(L(X^n) > \tau )\} and \gamma  = \frac {\alpha  - \mathbb {P}(L(X^n) > \tau )}{\mathbb {P}(L(X^n) = \tau )}

